<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-inscribed-circles" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Inscribed Circles</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.3 Circles, Chords and Tangents
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                            <ul>
                              <li>Construct an inscribed, circumscribed and escribed circles on a triangle</li>
                              <li>Determine the centroid and orthocentre of a triangle</li>
                            </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    12 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To guide learners to discover the incenter by asking: <em>what is the largest circle that fits inside a triangle?</em> Learners experiment with circle placement, then reason their way to the angle bisector construction.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Resist giving the answer to part (a). Let learners place the centre intuitively first — most will not choose the same point, which makes part (b) productive. When circulating, prompt with: <q>If your circle is touching one side but not another, can you shift the centre to make it bigger?</q> The key insight in part (c) is that if the centre is closer to one side than another, there is room to shift it away from the nearest side, increasing the radius. This motivates equidistance — and from there, angle bisectors.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>The Largest Circle Inside a Triangle</title>
                <p>
                    In this activity you will investigate where to place a circle so that it fits inside a triangle as large as possible.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Draw a triangle <m>ABC</m> of your choice using a ruler (no need for a specific size). Using a compass, try to draw the largest circle you can that fits <em>completely inside</em> the triangle — the circle must not cross any side. Mark the centre you used and record the radius.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Compare your circle with a classmate's. Did you choose the same centre? Who has the larger radius? Try adjusting your centre to see if you can do better.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Think about why the best centre must be <em>equidistant from all three sides</em>. If the circle is closer to one side than the others, explain why you could shift the centre slightly to increase the radius.
                            </p>
                            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                                <p>
                                    If the distance to one side is less than the distance to another, the circle's radius is limited by the nearest side. Shifting the centre away from the nearest side (while staying away from the other two) increases the minimum distance, allowing a larger circle. The optimal centre is where all three distances are equal.
                                </p>
                            </solution>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Now use a systematic construction. Bisect angle <m>A</m> — recall that every point on an angle bisector is equidistant from the two sides of that angle. Bisect angle <m>B</m>. Label the intersection of the two bisectors <m>I</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Drop a perpendicular from <m>I</m> to each side of the triangle. Measure all three perpendicular distances <m>d_1</m>, <m>d_2</m>, <m>d_3</m> in millimetres and record them in the table below.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Draw a circle with centre <m>I</m> and radius equal to the common perpendicular distance. Does it touch all three sides? Is it larger than the circle you drew in part (a)?
                            </p>
                            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                                <p>
                                    The three distances should agree to within measurement error. The circle will be tangent to all three sides, and will be the largest possible circle fitting inside the triangle.
                                </p>
                            </solution>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <table>
                    <title>Perpendicular distances from incenter to each side</title>
                    <tabular halign="center" top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
                        <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                            <cell>Triangle</cell>
                            <cell><m>d_1</m> (mm)</cell>
                            <cell><m>d_2</m> (mm)</cell>
                            <cell><m>d_3</m> (mm)</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>1</cell>
                            <cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>2</cell>
                            <cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>3</cell>
                            <cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
            </paragraphs>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalise the incenter construction and introduce the inradius formula <m>r = \text{Area}/s</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Ask a few learners to share their three distances. Confirm they are (approximately) equal. Tell learners: <q>This point <m>I</m> is called the <term>incenter</term>. The circle we drew is the <term>inscribed circle</term>, or <term>incircle</term>, and its radius is called the <term>inradius</term>.</q>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Emphasise that the incenter is always inside the triangle (unlike the circumcenter, which can be outside for obtuse triangles).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Present the key formula: the triangle can be cut into three smaller triangles by joining <m>I</m> to each vertex. Each has a side of the original triangle as its base and <m>r</m> as its height, giving <m>\text{Area} = r \cdot s</m>, so <m>r = \text{Area}/s</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-inscribed-circle">
        <title>The Incircle and Inradius</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The three angle bisectors of any triangle meet at a single point <m>I</m>, called the <term>incenter</term>. The circle centred at <m>I</m> that is tangent to all three sides is the <term>inscribed circle</term> (or <term>incircle</term>). Its radius, the <term>inradius</term> <m>r</m>, satisfies
                <md>
                    r = \frac{\text{Area}}{s},
                </md>
                where <m>s = \tfrac{1}{2}(a+b+c)</m> is the semi-perimeter of the triangle.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-theorem">
                <caption>Triangle <m>ABC</m> with its inscribed circle. The incircle, centred at <m>I</m>, is tangent to all three sides; the perpendicular distance from <m>I</m> to each side equals <m>r</m>.</caption>
                <image width="60%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1/4/A}
                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                            \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto C--A](I)\tkzGetPoint{Y}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto A--B](I)\tkzGetPoint{Z}
                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                            \tkzDrawSegments[dashed](I,X I,Y I,Z)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](I,X,C)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](I,Y,A)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](I,Z,B)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,I,X,Y,Z)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](I)
                            \tkzLabelSegment[right](I,X){$r$}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                Join <m>I</m> to each vertex, dividing triangle <m>ABC</m> into three smaller triangles: <m>\triangle IBC</m>, <m>\triangle ICA</m>, and <m>\triangle IAB</m>. Because <m>I</m> is the incenter, its perpendicular distance to every side equals <m>r</m>. Using base <m>\times</m> height for each smaller triangle:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Area}(\triangle IBC) \amp= \tfrac{1}{2} a r,</mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Area}(\triangle ICA) \amp= \tfrac{1}{2} b r,</mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Area}(\triangle IAB) \amp= \tfrac{1}{2} c r.</mrow>
                </md>
                Adding these and using <m>s = \tfrac{1}{2}(a+b+c)</m>:
                <md>
                    \text{Area} = \tfrac{1}{2}r(a+b+c) = r \cdot s.
                </md>
                Dividing both sides by <m>s</m> gives <m>r = \text{Area}/s</m>.
            </p>
        </proof>
    </theorem>

    <insight>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>The incenter</term> is the intersection of the three angle bisectors. It is equidistant from all three sides of the triangle.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Inradius formula:</term>
                        <md>
                            r = \frac{\text{Area}}{s}, \qquad \text{equivalently} \qquad \text{Area} = r \cdot s,
                        </md>
                        where <m>s = \tfrac{1}{2}(a+b+c)</m> is the semi-perimeter.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Right-triangle shortcut:</term> for a right triangle with legs <m>a</m>, <m>b</m> and hypotenuse <m>c</m>,
                        <md>
                            r = \frac{a + b - c}{2}.
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Tangent segment lengths:</term> if the incircle touches side <m>BC</m> at <m>X</m>, side <m>CA</m> at <m>Y</m>, and side <m>AB</m> at <m>Z</m>, then
                        <md>
                            AY = AZ = s - a, \quad BX = BZ = s - b, \quad CX = CY = s - c.
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <paragraphs>
        <title>Constructing the Inscribed Circle</title>
        <p>
            To construct the inscribed circle of a triangle using only a pair of compasses and a straightedge, follow these steps.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Draw triangle <m>ABC</m>.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-con-step1">
                        <caption>Step 1: Triangle <m>ABC</m>.</caption>
                        <image width="50%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1.5/4/A}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Bisect angle <m>A</m>: place the compass point at <m>A</m> and draw an arc that crosses both sides <m>AB</m> and <m>AC</m>. Label the crossing points <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-con-step2">
                        <caption>Step 2: Arc from <m>A</m> crossing sides <m>AB</m> at <m>P</m> and <m>AC</m> at <m>Q</m>.</caption>
                        <image width="50%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1.5/4/A}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center A ratio 0.5](B)\tkzGetPoint{P}
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center A ratio 0.5](C)\tkzGetPoint{Q}
                                    \draw[dashed, gray] (P) arc[start angle=220, end angle=310, radius=2.06];
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(P,Q)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[left](P)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Without changing the compass width, place the compass point at <m>P</m> and draw an arc inside the triangle. Then place the compass point at <m>Q</m> and draw a crossing arc. Label the intersection <m>D</m>. Draw the ray <m>AD</m> — this is the bisector of angle <m>A</m>.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-con-step3">
                        <caption>Step 3: Arcs from <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> meet at <m>D</m>; ray <m>AD</m> bisects angle <m>A</m>.</caption>
                        <image width="50%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1.5/4/A}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center A ratio 0.5](B)\tkzGetPoint{P}
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center A ratio 0.5](C)\tkzGetPoint{Q}
                                    \draw[dashed, gray] (P) arc[start angle=220, end angle=310, radius=2.06];
                                    \tkzDefLine[bisector](B,A,C)\tkzGetPoint{D}
                                    \draw[dashed, gray] (P) arc[start angle=258, end angle=320, radius=1.0];
                                    \draw[dashed, gray] (Q) arc[start angle=195, end angle=258, radius=1.0];
                                    \draw[teal, dashed, thick] (A) -- (D);
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(P,Q,D)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[left](P)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below](D)
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Repeat the same process for angle <m>B</m>: draw an arc from <m>B</m> crossing sides <m>BA</m> and <m>BC</m>, then draw crossing arcs to find a point, and draw the bisector ray from <m>B</m>. Label the point where the two bisector rays meet as <m>I</m> — this is the <term>incenter</term>.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-con-step4">
                        <caption>Step 4: Bisectors of angles <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> meet at the incenter <m>I</m>.</caption>
                        <image width="50%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1.5/4/A}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                    \tkzDefLine[bisector](B,A,C)\tkzGetPoint{Da}
                                    \tkzDefLine[bisector](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{Db}
                                    \draw[teal, dashed, thick] (A) -- (Da);
                                    \draw[teal, dashed, thick] (B) -- (Db);
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        From <m>I</m>, drop a perpendicular to one side of the triangle (for example, to side <m>BC</m>). To do this with a compass: place the compass at <m>I</m> and draw arcs crossing <m>BC</m> on both sides; then bisect the segment between the two crossing points to find the foot. Label the foot <m>X</m>. The distance <m>IX</m> is the inradius <m>r</m>.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-con-step5">
                        <caption>Step 5: Perpendicular from <m>I</m> to side <m>BC</m>, with foot <m>X</m>. The length <m>IX = r</m>.</caption>
                        <image width="50%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1.5/4/A}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                    \tkzDrawSegment[dashed](I,X)
                                    \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](I,X,C)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(I,X)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below](X)
                                    \tkzLabelSegment[right](I,X){$r$}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Set your compass to radius <m>r = IX</m>. Place the compass point at <m>I</m> and draw the circle. This circle touches all three sides of the triangle and is the inscribed circle.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-con-step6">
                        <caption>Step 6: The completed inscribed circle with centre <m>I</m> and radius <m>r</m>, tangent to all three sides.</caption>
                        <image width="50%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1.5/4/A}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                    \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
        <title>The Centroid</title>
        <p>
            A <term>median</term> of a triangle is a line segment joining a vertex to the midpoint of the opposite side. Every triangle has three medians, and they always meet at a single point called the <term>centroid</term>, usually labelled <m>G</m>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-centroid-triangle">
            <caption>Triangle <m>ABC</m> with its three medians meeting at the centroid <m>G</m>. Each median joins a vertex to the midpoint of the opposite side.</caption>
            <image width="60%">
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1/4/A}
                        \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                        \tkzDefMidPoint(B,C)\tkzGetPoint{Ma}
                        \tkzDefMidPoint(C,A)\tkzGetPoint{Mb}
                        \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B)\tkzGetPoint{Mc}
                        \tkzDefTriangleCenter[centroid](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{G}
                        \tkzDrawSegments[teal, thick](A,Ma B,Mb C,Mc)
                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,Ma,Mb,Mc,G)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[below](Ma)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[right](Mb)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[left](Mc)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[above right](G)
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
        <p>
            The centroid has a special property: it divides each median in the ratio <m>2:1</m> from the vertex. So if the median from <m>A</m> has length <m>m_a</m>, then <m>AG = \tfrac{2}{3}m_a</m> and <m>GM_a = \tfrac{1}{3}m_a</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Physically, the centroid is the <em>balance point</em> of the triangle: a uniform triangular lamina (flat plate) would balance on a pin placed exactly at <m>G</m>. The centroid is always inside the triangle, regardless of whether the triangle is acute, right, or obtuse.
        </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
        <title>The Orthocentre</title>
        <p>
            An <term>altitude</term> of a triangle is the perpendicular from a vertex to the line containing the opposite side. The three altitudes of a triangle always meet at a single point called the <term>orthocentre</term>, usually labelled <m>H</m>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-orthocentre-triangle">
            <caption>An acute triangle <m>ABC</m> with its three altitudes meeting at the orthocentre <m>H</m>. Right-angle marks show each altitude is perpendicular to the opposite side.</caption>
            <image width="60%">
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 2/4/A}
                        \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                        \tkzDefTriangleCenter[ortho](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{H}
                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](A)\tkzGetPoint{Ha}
                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto A--C](B)\tkzGetPoint{Hb}
                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto A--B](C)\tkzGetPoint{Hc}
                        \tkzDrawSegments[teal, thick](A,Ha B,Hb C,Hc)
                        \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](A,Ha,C)
                        \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](B,Hb,C)
                        \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](C,Hc,B)
                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,H,Ha,Hb,Hc)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[above right](H)
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
        <p>
            The position of <m>H</m> depends on the type of triangle:
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        In an <em>acute triangle</em>, <m>H</m> lies <em>inside</em> the triangle.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        In a <em>right triangle</em>, <m>H</m> is at the <em>vertex of the right angle</em> (the two legs are themselves altitudes).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        In an <em>obtuse triangle</em>, <m>H</m> lies <em>outside</em> the triangle, on the far side of the obtuse vertex.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A triangle has sides <m>3</m> cm, <m>4</m> cm, and <m>5</m> cm. Find the radius of its inscribed circle.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-3-4-5">
                <caption>The <m>3</m>-<m>4</m>-<m>5</m> right triangle with its inscribed circle of radius <m>r = 1</m> cm.</caption>
                <image width="55%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 0/3/A}
                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.2](A,B,C)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above left](A)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                            \tkzLabelSegment[left](B,A){$3$ cm}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[below](B,C){$4$ cm}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[right](A,C){$5$ cm}
                            \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                First check: <m>3^2 + 4^2 = 9 + 16 = 25 = 5^2</m>, so this is a right triangle with hypotenuse <m>c = 5</m> cm.
            </p>
            <p>
                <em>Method 1 — inradius formula.</em>
                <md>
                    <mrow>s \amp= \frac{3+4+5}{2} = 6 \text{ cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Area} \amp= \tfrac{1}{2} \times 3 \times 4 = 6 \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>r \amp= \frac{\text{Area}}{s} = \frac{6}{6} = 1 \text{ cm}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                <em>Method 2 — right-triangle shortcut.</em>
                <md>
                    r = \frac{a+b-c}{2} = \frac{3+4-5}{2} = \frac{2}{2} = 1 \text{ cm.}
                </md>
                Both methods agree: the inradius is <m>\boxed{1}</m> cm.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A triangle has sides <m>5</m> cm, <m>12</m> cm, and <m>13</m> cm.
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>Find the inradius.</li>
                    <li>The incircle touches side <m>QR = 13</m> cm at point <m>X</m>, and the opposite vertex is <m>P</m>. Find the tangent length <m>PX'</m> from <m>P</m> to its tangent point.</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-5-12-13">
                <caption>Triangle <m>PQR</m> with <m>PQ = 5</m>, <m>PR = 12</m>, <m>QR = 13</m>. The incircle touches sides <m>PQ</m> and <m>PR</m> at <m>Y</m> and <m>Z</m> respectively; the tangent lengths from <m>P</m> are each <m>2</m> cm.</caption>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.75]
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/Q, 12/0/R, 0/5/P}
                            \tkzDrawPolygon(P,Q,R)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.25](R,Q,P)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above left](P)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](Q)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](R)
                            \tkzLabelSegment[left](Q,P){$5$ cm}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[below](Q,R){$13$ cm}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[right](P,R){$12$ cm}
                            \tkzDefCircle[in](P,Q,R)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto Q--R](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto P--Q](I)\tkzGetPoint{Y}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto P--R](I)\tkzGetPoint{Z}
                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(I,X,Y,Z)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[left](Y)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above right](Z)
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                (a) Check: <m>5^2+12^2 = 25+144 = 169 = 13^2</m>, so the triangle is right-angled.
                <md>
                    <mrow>s \amp= \frac{5+12+13}{2} = 15 \text{ cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Area} \amp= \tfrac{1}{2}\times 5 \times 12 = 30 \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>r \amp= \frac{30}{15} = 2 \text{ cm}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                (b) Label the triangle so that <m>PQ = 5</m>, <m>PR = 12</m>, <m>QR = 13</m>. Using the tangent length formula with <m>a = QR = 13</m>:
                <md>
                    PY = PZ = s - a = 15 - 13 = 2 \text{ cm.}
                </md>
                The tangent length from <m>P</m> to its tangent point is <m>2</m> cm.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A triangular plot of land in Kiambu has sides <m>30</m> m, <m>40</m> m, and <m>50</m> m. A farmer wants to install a circular irrigation pond that fits inside the plot and just touches all three boundaries. Find the radius of the pond.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-30-40-50">
                <caption>The triangular plot with sides <m>30</m> m, <m>40</m> m, <m>50</m> m. The inscribed circle represents the irrigation pond of radius <m>10</m> m.</caption>
                <image width="55%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 0/3/A}
                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.2](A,B,C)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above left](A)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                            \tkzLabelSegment[left](B,A){$30$ m}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[below](B,C){$40$ m}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[right](A,C){$50$ m}
                            \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                            \tkzDrawSegments[dashed](I,X)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](I,X,C)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(I,X)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above right](I)
                            \tkzLabelSegment[right](I,X){$r$}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Check: <m>30^2+40^2 = 900+1600 = 2500 = 50^2</m>, so the plot is a right triangle.
                <md>
                    <mrow>s \amp= \frac{30+40+50}{2} = 60 \text{ m}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Area} \amp= \tfrac{1}{2}\times 30 \times 40 = 600 \text{ m}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>r \amp= \frac{600}{60} = 10 \text{ m}</mrow>
                </md>
                The pond should have a radius of <m>10</m> m.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A triangle has a perimeter of <m>36</m> cm and an inscribed circle of radius <m>3</m> cm. Find the area of the triangle.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The semi-perimeter is <m>s = 36/2 = 18</m> cm. Using <m>\text{Area} = r \cdot s</m>:
                <md>
                    \text{Area} = 3 \times 18 = 54 \text{ cm}^2.
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the inradius of a triangle with sides <m>6</m> cm, <m>8</m> cm, and <m>10</m> cm.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-ex1">
                    <caption>Right triangle with sides <m>6</m>, <m>8</m>, <m>10</m> cm and its incircle.</caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 0/3/A}
                                \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.2](A,B,C)
                                \tkzLabelSegment[left](B,A){$6$ cm}
                                \tkzLabelSegment[below](B,C){$8$ cm}
                                \tkzLabelSegment[right](A,C){$10$ cm}
                                \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Check: <m>6^2+8^2 = 36+64 = 100 = 10^2</m> (right triangle).
                    <md>
                        <mrow>s \amp= \frac{6+8+10}{2} = 12 \text{ cm}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{Area} \amp= \tfrac{1}{2}\times 6 \times 8 = 24 \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
                        <mrow>r \amp= \frac{24}{12} = 2 \text{ cm}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A triangle has sides <m>7</m> cm, <m>15</m> cm, and <m>20</m> cm. Calculate its inradius.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-ex2">
                    <caption>Scalene triangle with sides <m>7</m>, <m>15</m>, <m>20</m> cm and its incircle.</caption>
                    <image width="55%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 0.5/3/A}
                                \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                \tkzLabelSegment[left](B,A){$7$ cm}
                                \tkzLabelSegment[below](B,C){$20$ cm}
                                \tkzLabelSegment[right](A,C){$15$ cm}
                                \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>s \amp= \frac{7+15+20}{2} = 21 \text{ cm}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{Area} \amp= \sqrt{21 \times 14 \times 6 \times 1} = \sqrt{1764} = 42 \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
                        <mrow>r \amp= \frac{42}{21} = 2 \text{ cm}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The incircle of a triangle has radius <m>4</m> cm, and the triangle has perimeter <m>48</m> cm. Find the area of the triangle.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-ex3">
                    <caption>A triangle with incircle of radius <m>r</m>.</caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 1.2/3.5/A}
                                \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                \tkzDrawSegments[dashed](I,X)
                                \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](I,X,C)
                                \tkzDrawPoints(I,X)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above right](I)
                                \tkzLabelSegment[right](I,X){$r$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        s = \frac{48}{2} = 24 \text{ cm}, \qquad \text{Area} = r \cdot s = 4 \times 24 = 96 \text{ cm}^2.
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In triangle <m>PQR</m>, <m>PQ = 13</m> cm, <m>QR = 14</m> cm, and <m>PR = 15</m> cm. The incircle touches side <m>QR</m> at <m>X</m>. Find the length <m>QX</m>.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-ex4">
                    <caption>Triangle <m>PQR</m> with its incircle. The incircle touches side <m>QR</m> at <m>X</m>.</caption>
                    <image width="55%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/Q, 4/0/R, 1.5/3.2/P}
                                \tkzDrawPolygon(P,Q,R)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above](P)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below left](Q)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](R)
                                \tkzDefCircle[in](P,Q,R)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto Q--R](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                \tkzDrawSegments[dashed](I,X)
                                \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](I,X,R)
                                \tkzDrawPoints(I,X)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above right](I)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below](X)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>s \amp= \frac{13+14+15}{2} = 21 \text{ cm}</mrow>
                        <mrow>QX \amp= s - PR = 21 - 15 = 6 \text{ cm}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A right triangle has legs <m>5</m> cm and <m>12</m> cm.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>Use the formula <m>r = \dfrac{a+b-c}{2}</m> to find the inradius.</li>
                        <li>Verify your answer using <m>r = \text{Area}/s</m>.</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-ex5">
                    <caption>Right triangle with legs <m>5</m> cm and <m>12</m> cm and its incircle.</caption>
                    <image width="60%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.75]
                                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/Q, 12/0/R, 0/5/P}
                                \tkzDrawPolygon(P,Q,R)
                                \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.25](R,Q,P)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above left](P)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below left](Q)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](R)
                                \tkzLabelSegment[left](Q,P){$5$ cm}
                                \tkzLabelSegment[below](Q,R){$12$ cm}
                                \tkzLabelSegment[right](P,R){$13$ cm}
                                \tkzDefCircle[in](P,Q,R)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto Q--R](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above right](I)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The hypotenuse is <m>c = \sqrt{5^2+12^2} = \sqrt{169} = 13</m> cm.
                </p>
                <p>
                    (a) <m>r = \dfrac{5+12-13}{2} = \dfrac{4}{2} = 2</m> cm.
                </p>
                <p>
                    (b) <m>s = \dfrac{5+12+13}{2} = 15</m> cm, Area <m>= \tfrac{1}{2}\times 5 \times 12 = 30</m> cm<m>^2</m>, so <m>r = 30/15 = 2</m> cm. <m>\checkmark</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For each triangle below, use a pair of compasses and a straightedge to construct the inscribed circle.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>Acute scalene triangle.</p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-ex-a1">
                                <caption>Acute scalene triangle <m>ABC</m>.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 1/3.5/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Right triangle.</p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-ex-a2">
                                <caption>Right triangle <m>ABC</m> with the right angle at <m>B</m>.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 0/3/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.2](A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above left](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Obtuse triangle.</p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-ex-a3">
                                <caption>Obtuse triangle <m>ABC</m>.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, -0.5/2.5/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[left](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Equilateral triangle.</p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-ex-a4">
                                <caption>Equilateral triangle <m>ABC</m>.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 2.5/4.33/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    In each case, bisect two angles to find the incenter <m>I</m>, then drop a perpendicular to one side to find the inradius, and draw the circle.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-sol-a1">
                                <caption>Acute scalene triangle with inscribed circle.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 1/3.5/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                            \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                            \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-sol-a2">
                                <caption>Right triangle with inscribed circle.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 0/3/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.2](A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above left](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                            \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                            \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-sol-a3">
                                <caption>Obtuse triangle with inscribed circle.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, -0.5/2.5/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[left](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                            \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                            \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-sol-a4">
                                <caption>Equilateral triangle with inscribed circle.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 2.5/4.33/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                            \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                            \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above right](I)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For each triangle below, use a pair of compasses and a straightedge to construct the inscribed circle.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>Acute isosceles triangle.</p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-ex-b1">
                                <caption>Acute isosceles triangle <m>ABC</m>.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 2/4/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Right triangle (scaled 5-12-13).</p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-ex-b2">
                                <caption>Right triangle <m>ABC</m> with the right angle at <m>B</m>.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 0/2.5/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.2](A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above left](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Wide obtuse triangle.</p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-ex-b3">
                                <caption>Wide obtuse triangle <m>ABC</m>.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1/1.5/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Narrow acute triangle.</p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-ex-b4">
                                <caption>Narrow acute triangle <m>ABC</m>.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 3/0/C, 1.5/4.5/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    In each case, bisect two angles to find the incenter <m>I</m>, then drop a perpendicular to one side to find the inradius, and draw the circle.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-sol-b1">
                                <caption>Acute isosceles triangle with inscribed circle.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 2/4/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                            \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                            \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-sol-b2">
                                <caption>Right triangle (scaled 5-12-13) with inscribed circle.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 0/2.5/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.2](A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above left](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                            \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                            \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-sol-b3">
                                <caption>Wide obtuse triangle with inscribed circle.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1/1.5/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                            \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                            \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above right](I)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-con-sol-b4">
                                <caption>Narrow acute triangle with inscribed circle.</caption>
                                <image width="48%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 3/0/C, 1.5/4.5/A}
                                            \tkzDrawPolygon(A,B,C)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                            \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{X}
                                            \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](I,X)
                                            \tkzDrawPoints(I)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](I)
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

